Brain structure which is caudally attached to the rostral medulla oblongata and extends into the tectal ventricle. The valvula cerebelli consists of a granular and a molecular layer along with aggregations of large Purkinje and eurydendroid cells and is uniquely present in ray-finned fishes. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

PreferredTerm: obsolete ventral rhombencephalic commissure brain stem

Description: Connective tissue partitions developing between the myotomes. Kimmel et al, 1995.
A brainstem commissure that contains major crossed descending projections from both tectal lobes.

Endochondral bone that is part of the antero-lateral region of the palate. Commonly, it articulates with the maxilla anterolaterally and with the ethmoidal region medially. It may also articulate with the dermopalatine ventro-laterally and with the entopterygoid posteriorly. The autopalatine is paired.
Surface structure which is a tactile structure found in the branchial region. Barbels are covered with epidermis rich in taste buds, and are innervated by branches of the cranial nerves.
basipterygium element that is composed of bone tissue.
Replacement bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates anteriorly with the anterior ceratohyal.
Caudal part of the abducens nucleus that mediates motor function.

PreferredTerm: caudal zone of median tuberal portion of hypothalamus

Description: Postcranial axial cartilage and Weberian ossicle that is located dorsal to the scaphium. The claustrum cartilage is bilaterally paired.
Part of the anterior commissure which is located immediately ventral to the supracommissural nucleus of area ventralis telencephali.

PreferredTerm: commissure of the secondary gustatory nuclei
obsolete decussation of the medial octavolateralis nucleus

Description: anal fin distal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
Musculature that is part of the dorsal fin.
Rostral part of the abducens nucleus that mediates motor function.
Dermal bone that forms the ventro-medial part of the palate and the antero-ventral and ventral wall of the orbit. The entopterygoid is a paired bone.
Dorsal branchial arch bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial cartilage or bone and medially with pharyngobranchial cartilage or bone.

A free, modified neural spine of a preural or a ural vertebra that is placed between the last developed neural spine of a preural centrum and the dorsal axis (= anterior margin of first uroneural) of the caudal skeleton . An epural commonly supports one or more dorsal procurrent rays. An epural is an unpaired median perichondrally ossified bone.

Dermal canal-bearing bone placed at the dorso-posterior region of the skull roof, lying on the posterior region of the pterotic and parietals, or the pterotic and epioccipital, or on the pterotic, epioccipital and occipital bones.

A pair of HA are connect one to each AA1. They run rostromedially until at the extreme rostro-ventral midline the two vessels merge and then run straight caudally along the ventral midline until they reach the cranial end of the ventral aorta (VA). There, the single HA passes just dorsal to the rostral end of the VA and then immediately splits again into a pair of HA. The paired HA continue caudally just to either side of the ventral midline. The HA provide blood supply to the ventral branchial region and the heart.sogai et al. 2001.

Dermal bone that is part of the opercular series. It is located ventro-medially to the preopercle and anterior to the subopercle. It is joined to the posterior part of the lower jaw (retroarticular) by a ligament. The interopercle is paired.
Specialized neuronal receptor cells of the lateral line and acoustico-vestibular systems. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for hair cells by T. Whitfield.)

Dermal bone that is part of the dorsal or upper border or antero-dorsal border of the orbit. The supraorbital bone may contact the orbital margin of the frontal bone medially, the antorbital antero-ventrally and the dermosphenotic posteriorly. The supraorbital bone does not carry sensory canals. The supraorbital bone is paired.
Replacement bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with the hyomandibula and the quadrate.
Tooth that forms on ceratobranchial 5 cartilage or bone.

Endochondral bone, membrane bone, and Weberian ossicle that is an element of third vertebra. Anteriorly it attaches to the interosseus ligament and posteriorly it extends as a transformator process embedded in the tunica externa of the swimbladder.
Process that is the dorsally directed, vertical process of the entopterygoid. The strut sometimes articulates with the orbitosphenoid.

A multilayer of deep cells of fairly uniform thickness that forms during early epiboly (at dome stage; upon conversion of the blastodisc to the blastoderm); during gastrulation the DEL (deep cell layer) gives rise to the epiblast and hypoblast. Kimmel et al, 1995.
The portion of the YSL that lies deep to the blastoderm during epiboly. Kimmel et al, 1995.

PreferredTerm: afferent portion of pharyngeal arch artery
Description: A section of a pharyngeal arch artery that delivers blood to the gills.

PreferredTerm: apical ectodermal ridge median fin fold
Description: Apical ectodermal ridge that is part of the median fin fold.
Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Somite-derived body wall muscle present dorsal to the horizontal myoseptum. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Undifferentiated mesodermal component of early trunk or tail segment or metamere, derived from paraxial mesoderm; forms the myotome, sclerotome and perhaps dermatome. Kimmel et al, 1995.

Caudal vertebra that is one of the last caudal vertebrae anterior to the ural vertebrae that with its neural and haemal spines supports the procurrent caudal fin rays or lepidotrichia. The numbering of preural vertebrae is from caudal to rostral direction.

Connect the outflow of the aortic arches to the dorsal aorta. The place where the lateral dorsal aorta fuse is is called the radiax of the aorta. Isogai et al. 2001.
The caudal fin is the most posterior median fin. It is composed of a complex of three modified centra and modified neural and hemal arches and spines. Mabee and Bird, 2001.

PreferredTerm: cranial division of the internal carotid artery

Description: Basidorsals are bilaterally paired cartilages on the dorsolateral side of the notochord which are replaced by ossified neural arches or dorsal arcocentra. In otophysan fishes, basidorsal 1, bd2, bd3, and bd4 give rise to parts of the Weberian apparatus.
precursor to mesencephalic artery
This anteriormost portion of the intestine has the most digestive enzymes and the greatest epithelial surface area. Wallace et al, 2005.
Annotation with this anatomy term indicates that a structure was not specified by the author.
An otic sensory epithelium that will develop into the mature macula.

Description: A protuberance in front of the gential pore and behind the vent. Mature females have a well developed urogenital papillae whilst in mature males it is poorly developed. Brion et al, 2004.
Postcranial axial skeleton that is unpaired and located on the sagittal plane of the organism.
Median fin skeleton located on the dorsal surface of the organism.
The dorsal marginal region of the YSL where maternal dorsal determinants localize. Participates in positioning the shield. Ho et al, 1999.

The NEM cell cluster lies in a superficial position of the dorsal blastoderm margin encompassing EVL cells and one or two layers of underlying deep cells. Unlike other marginal blastomeres, cells in this cluster do not participate in involution. Cooper et al, 1996.
Tooth row that is the ventralmost row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone.
Tooth row that is the mediodorsal row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone, located between the dorsal tooth row and ventral tooth row.
Tooth row that is the dorsalmost row of teeth on ceratobranchial 5 bone.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the anteriormost tooth in the ventral tooth row.

Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the dorsal tooth row.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is the posteriormost tooth in the mediodorsal tooth row.
Ceratobranchial 5 tooth which is posterior to tooth 2MD and anterior to tooth 4MD in the mediodorsal tooth row.

A migrating group of cells originating from the posterior lateral line placode. The primordium deposits seven to nine neuromasts and interneuromasts between them during its posterior migration to the tail. Gompel et al, 2001.
Scute that is a bony plate that forms in dorsal midline of body margin between the skull and dorsal fin.
Median fin that is located posterior to the anus.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 1.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 2.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 5.
Endochondral bone and Weberian ossicle that is an element of the fourth vertebra that curves ventrally around the anterior head of the swim bladder.
Cartilaginous larval structure dorsal to the four anterior-most vertebrae, which forms the connection between neural arches and supraneurals in the Weberian apparatus. Bird and Mabee, 2003.

A layer of collagen fibrils present in the imature integument in an acellular subepidermal space. At first, the fibrils are all oriented in the same direction, later they form the complex plywood-like structure that is characteristic of the dermal deep region. Le Guellec et al, 2004.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the anteriormost vertebrae and associated structures that connect the swim bladder to the inner ear.
Vertebra that is part of the Weberian apparatus.
Supraneural bone located dorsal to vertebra 2.
Supraneural bone that is located dorsal to vertebrae 3 and 4.

Islands of eosinic cells found on the lateroventral surface of the kidney. Function is thought to be that of the parathyroid gland in other vertebrates, which are lacking in fishes. These cells secrete hypocalcin (teleocalcin) to regulate calcium metabolism.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with more than one pharyngeal arch in the pharyngeal arch 3-7 skeleton.
Copula that is ventral, median, and associated with pharyngeal arches 3-5.
Copula that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arches 4 and 5 (pharyngeal arches 6-7).
Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 1 (pharyngeal arch 3). Typically develops in the anterior copula cartilage.
Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 2 (pharyngeal arch 4). Typically develops in the anterior copula cartilage.
Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 3 (pharyngeal arch 5). Typically develops in the anterior copula cartilage.
Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 4 (pharyngeal arch 6). Develops in posterior copula cartilage or basibranchial 4 cartilage.
Hypobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 1 element laterally. Develops in hypobranchial 1 cartilage.
Hypobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 4 element laterally. Develops in hypobranchial 4 cartilage.
Hypobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 3 element laterally. Develops in hypobranchial 3 cartilage.
Hypobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 2 element laterally. Develops in hypobranchial 2 cartilage.
Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial bone that is the most posterior, bilaterally paired ventral pharyngeal arch bone.
Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone and medially with pharyngobranchial cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and located at the articulation of epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone and the posterior tip of ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone and medially with pharyngobranchial cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone and medially with pharyngobranchial cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial bone that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 3 cartilage or bone and medially with pharyngobranchial cartilage or bone.
Pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.
Most posterior pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials.
Pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.
Neural arch that is the second after the neurocranium.
The medial portion of the spinal cord floor plate, located adjacent to the notochord.
Stage I follicles (less than 140 microns) are primary growth stage. Selman et al, 1993.
Stage II follicles (140-340 microns) are cortical alveolus stage. Selman et al, 1993.
Stage III (340-690 microns) are vitellogenesis. Selman et al, 1993.
Fin or limb undergoing the process of regeneration.

Tendon bone located on the median side of the lower jaw, dorsal to Meckel's cartilage and medial to the angular. The coronomeckelian forms as an ossification of the tendon of the adductor mandibulae muscle. The coronomeckelian is a paired bone.
Endochondral bone that is the median element of the ventral hyoid arch, generally lying between the paired ventral hypohyals.

The anterior compartment of the swim bladder is thought to have acoustic resonance properties that play a key role in audition. It is connected to the posterior chamber via the dusctus communicans. Finney et al, 2006.
The posterior compartment of the swim bladder plays a key role in buoyancy control. It is connected to the anterior chamber via the dusctus communicans. Finney et al, 2006.
Branchiostegal ray that is the anterior-most ray in the adult.
Branchiostegal ray that is the third anterior-most ray in the adult.
Branchiostegal ray that is the second anterior-most ray in the adult.
The posterior lateral line ganglion develops from a cranial ectodermal placode and contains sensory neurons that innervate the posterior lateral line system.
Dorsolateral placode that gives rise to the anterior lateral line.
A tract originating in the epiphysis and fasiculating with the tract of the postoptic commissure. Ross et al, 1992.
Sublingual that is the single element resulting from the fusion of the sublingual dorsal ossification and sublingual ventral ossification.
Supradorsals are small paired nodules of cartilage positioned at the distal ends of neural arches and the proximal end of neural spines (Arratia et al., 2001).

PreferredTerm: obsolete nucleus of the tract of the anterior commissure
Description: Telencephalic nucleus containing the cell bodies of neurons whose axons form the anterior commissure.

PreferredTerm: nucleus of the tract of the postoptic commissure
Description: The nucleus containing the cell bodies of neurons whose axons form the postoptic commissure.
A zone of delayed differentiation at the midbrainhindbrain boundary. The IZ separates midbrain from anterior hindbrain neuronal clusters and has been described in all vertebrates. Geling et al, 2003.
An unpaired left-sided accessory organ which plays a role in establishing lateral brain left right asymmetry. Gamse et al, 2003.
Basiventrals are bilaterally paired cartilages lateral to the notochord which are replaced by ossified parapophyses or hemal arches.
Anatomical cluster that consists of supraneural 2 bone and supraneural 3 bone and their extensions, and which is part of the Weberian apparatus.
Hemal spines are extensions of hemal arches in the ventral skeletogenous septum of the caudal region.

PreferredTerm: obsolete migratory slow muscle precursor cell
Description: Cells that initially are located adjacent to the spinal cord and notochord along that migrate from their initial medial position radially through the myotome to the lateral surface of the somites.

Epibranchials 1-3 in adults are compound elements formed by the fusion of epibranchial cartilages and the so-called uncinate processes. Posteromedially directed uncinate processes develop on the posterior edge of epibranchials 1-3. These appear as separate centers of chondrification (6.2 mm) that later fuse laterally to the posterior edges of the epibranchial cartilages (6.8 mm).

PreferredTerm: epithelial mesenchymal boundary of regenerating fin/limb
Description: A epithelial-mesenchymal boundary that is part of a regenerating fin/limb.
A epithelium that is part of a regenerating fin/limb.
The anteror lateral line ganglia develops from cranial ectodermal placodes and contain sensory neurons that innervate the anterior lateral line system.
Parapophysis that is the lateral projections from the first centrum in cyprinids, absent in catostomids, and absent in characiphysans (Fink and Fink, 1996).
Parapophysis that is lateral projection from the second centrum, absent in Siluriformes (Fink and Fink, 1996).
Neural arch 3 is expanded and fused to supraneural 3 as part of a neural complex roofing and protecting the neural canal.
Neural arch 4 is expanded and fused to supraneural 3 as part of the neural complex. A reduced neural spine projects from the posterior margin of the neural complex.
The parapophysis + rib, fused to the centrum, extends laterally then angles anteroventrally. A thin plate, the os suspensorium fuses to its median surface.
Posterior to the Weberian apparatus, otophysan supraneurals form as median, unpaired, rod- or platelike elements, as in other actinopterygians.

Dermal bone that first appears as paired ossifications in the membrane (dermis) dorsolateral to the ethmoid cartilage and anterolateral to the lateral ethmoids, later having the appearance of one butterfly-shaped element. Fused to the anterodorsal margin of the mesethmoid. Bordered anteriorly by the kinethmoid and posteriorly by the frontal.
Small rounded to egg-shaped cartilage bone that sits in an anterolateral depression on the prevomer. Articulates with the autopalatine in all cypriniforms.
Sesamoid bone located in the premaxillary-ethmoid ligament, between the mesethmoid and the premaxilla. The kinethmoid is an unpaired median bone.
Infraorbital that is the second bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the third bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the fourth bone of the infraorbital series.

Endochondral bone that borders that medial edge of the posttemporal fossa. The epiotics are sutured to parietals and supraoccipital dorsally, the exoccipitals ventrally and the pterotics laterally. The epiotic is a paired bone.
pelvic fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pelvic fin distal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pelvic fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.
Lepidotrichium which is part of the dorsal fin.
A range of seven to nine rod-like internal median skeletal support structures of the dorsal fin, comprised of both bone and cartilage and found between vertebrae 11 and 18.
A range of twelve to fourteen rod-like internal median skeletal support structures of the anal fin, comprised of both bone and cartilage and found between vertebrae 14 and 21.
Lepidotrichium which is part of the anal fin.
A duct connecting the esophagus to the posterior chamber of the swim bladder. Finney et al, 2006.
Sclerotic bone that is located anterior to the eye.
Sclerotic bone that is located posterior to the eye.

The constriction between the anterior and posterior chambers of the swim bladder. There does not appear to be an identifiable sphincter in the ductus, and therefore other musculature may regulate its opening. Finney et al, 2006.
Apical ectodermal ridge that is part of the pelvic fin.

A plate-like chondrogenic condensation within the pectoral fin, which subdivides into individual radials by decomposition of extracellular matrix in the inter-radial mesenchyme (Grandel and Schulte-Merker, 1998).
Cartilage which is part of the axial skeleton.

The anterior lateral line system develops from cranial ectodermal placodes, situated between the eye and the ear, that give rise to both the neuromasts and the anterior lateral line sensory nerves that innervate the neuromasts. The anterior lateral line system consists of small sensory patches (neuromasts) located superficially on the skin or just under the skin in fluid-filled canals on the head of all fishes and most amphibians and are innervated by several lateral line nerves, which project to the hindbrain. The anterior lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance.

The anterior lateral line consists of small sensory patches (neuromasts) located superficially on the skin or just under the skin in fluid-filled canals on the head of all fishes and most amphibians. The anterior lateral line develops from cranial ectodermal placodes situated between the eye and ear.

The posterior lateral line system develops from cranial ectodermal placodes, situated behind the ear, that give rise to both the neuromasts and the posterior lateral line sensory nerves that innervate the neuromasts. The posterior lateral line system consists of small sensory patches (neuromasts) located superficially on the skin or just under the skin in fluid-filled canals on the head of all fishes and most amphibians. The neuromasts are innervated by several lateral line nerves, which project primarily to the hindbrain. The posterior mechanosensory lateral line system is stimulated by local water displacements and vibrations, and detects propulsion of the fish through the water, as well as facilitating shoaling, prey capture, and predator and obstacle avoidance.
Neuromast that is part of the anterior lateral line. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)
Cells (completely cleaved), located underneath the superficial blastomeres and internal to the marginal blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.
Anatomical cluster consisting of the paired sublingual dorsal ossification and sublingual ventral ossification.
Sublingual that is the dorsal element paired with the sublingual ventral ossification.
Sublingual that is the ventral element paired with the sublingual dorsal ossification.
Nerve fibers originating from the dorsal anterior lateral line ganglion. These rami innervate the otic, supraorbital, and infraorbital neuromasts.
Nerve fibers originating from the ventral anterior lateral line ganglion. These rami innervate the mandibular and opercular neuromasts.
Nerve fibers originating from the middle lateral line ganglion. These fibers innervate the middle lateral line.
The middle lateral line ganglion develops from a cranial ectodermal placode and contains sensory neurons that innervate the middle lateral line.
Cells (completely cleaved), located at the surface of the blastodisc, above the deep blastomeres. Kimmel et al, 1995.

Bilaterally paired medial bar of cartilage formed at midorbit through medial chondrification from triangles of cartilage that later form the junction of the taeniae marginales anterior, taeniae marginales posterior and the epiphyseal bar.

Cranial cartilage which is a paired anterodorsal projection of the posterior end of the parachordal cartilage. It lies lateral to the notochord, just anterior to the posterior tip of the otic capsule. The bilaterally paired occipital arch cartilages fuse anterodorsally to the posterior edges of the auditory capsules and meet medially as the tectum synoticum (by 12 dpf).
Cartilage bar (bilaterally paired) that grows anteroventrally from the epiphyseal bar to join the anterolatera1 edge of the ethmoid plate.
Cartilage formed via medial fusion between bilaterally paired trabecula crani.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.

Cartilage bar (bilaterally paired) that is first visible as an anterior extension of the auditory capsule. It grows anteriorly toward the middle of the orbit where it is connected to its mate on the other side by the epiphyseal bar.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that forms the largest skeletal element of the ventral branchial arches.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with epibranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Ceratobranchial cartilage that is the most posterior, bilaterally paired ventral pharyngeal arch cartilage.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Hypobranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 1 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 3 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 2 cartilage or bone.
Epibranchial cartilage that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial 4 cartilage or bone.
Sublingual cartilage that is the dorsal element paired with the sublingual ventral cartilage.
Paired cartilages that project medially from the medial tips of epibranchials.
Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.
Pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.
Pectoral fin cartilage that is part of the embryonic primary pectoral girdle from which the mesocoracoid bone will ossify endochondrally.
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium.

Bilaterally paired small, rodlike cartilages on the ventral surface of the abdomen (present at 7.9 mm). Their posterior tips expand laterally, forming L-shaped cartilages. Medially, a posterior spur of cartilage develops, which will later ossify as the ischiac process (Weitzman 1962).
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior and medial edge of the basipterygium.
Small cartilage with a long posterior process and a shorter lateral one that forms at the posterior edge of the basipterygium, between radial cartilages 1 and 2.
Small cartilage that forms at the posterior and lateral edge of the basipterygium.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is the median cartilage of the ventral hyoid arch, generally lying between the paired ventral hypohyals.
Sublingual cartilage that is the ventral element paired with the sublingual dorsal cartilage.
Neural spine that is associated with the fourth vertebra.

Scute that is a bony plate that forms in the midline of ventral body margin between pectoral girdle and anal fin. Abdominal scutes may be present both anterior to and posterior to the pelvic girdle and fin.
Lepidotrichium which is part of the caudal fin.

Lepidotrichium which is part of the pectoral fin, forming the pectoral fin skeleton and articulating with the pectoral radials. A pectoral lepidotrichium is composed of two hemitrichia that surround bundles of actinotrichia distally.
Lepidotrichium which is part of the pelvic fin.

Dermal bone that is rod-like, formed and usually contained in a fin membrane, and jointed to or adjacent to distal radials. Lepidotrichia are formed from paired hemitrichia surrounding actinotrichia. There are usually two more lepidotrichia than distal radials.
Process of the premaxilla that extends posteriorly and overlays the mesethmoid.

In cypriniforms the anterior portion of the palatine has a dorsomedial process which abuts against the mesethmoid. Such a process is not present in other ostariophysans or in other primitive teleosts.

Ural vertebra that is the second vertebra posterior to preural centrum 1. It may bear a rudimentary neural arch and sometimes a rudimentary spine or the neural arch and spine are completely absent and it may articulate or fuse with hypural 2 (polyural terminology). Ural vertebra 2 is an unpaired median bone.
A vertebral centrum that is located immediately posterior to ural centrum 1. Ural centrum 2 is an unpaired median bone.
Urostyle that is the result of fusion of preural centrum 1 with the first ural centrum (of polyural terminology).

Caudal fin lepidotrichium that form part of the anterior dorsal and ventral series of lepidotrichia of the caudal fin that may be associated with a neural spine or an epural or an uroneural (dorsal series) and with a haemal spine of a preural vertebra (ventral series). Caudal procurrent rays are shorter than the caudal principal rays. A caudal procurrent ray is an unpaired median bone.

Caudal fin lepidotrichium that is adjacent to a branched ray. Caudal principal rays may be segmented but unbranched and the main element forming the dorsal or ventral leading margin of the caudal fin or a ray that may be only segmented-and-branched and forms part of the middle-posterior region of the fin. A caudal principal ray is an unpaired median bone.
pectoral fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin proximal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin distal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.

The propterygium is the lateralmost or anteriormost basal cartilage that originates from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc. The bases of the pectoral lepidotrichium 1 plus the propterygium articulates with the scapula.
Endochondral bone, membrane bone, and Weberian ossicle that is located dorsal to the scaphium. The claustrum bone is bilaterally paired.
Surface structure that is the dorsal portion of the caudal fin.
Surface structure that is the ventral portion of the caudal fin.
Process that is the upper portion of the maxilla that rests on the posterior surface of the lateral portion of the premaxilla.
Lateral bony projection proximal to lateral ethmoid-palatine joint, and located anterior to orbital region and posterior to olfactory region.
Scute that is a median bony plate forming anterior to procurrent caudal fin rays.
Process that is the paired process of the parasphenoid that articulates with the suspensorium.
Joint that articulates the autopalatine and lateral ethmoid and bones. Autopalatine-lateral ethmoid joint is paired.
Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 2 bone.
An endochondral bone that is the dorsally-oriented bony extension of the quadrate, extending from the anterior portion of the bone.
Process that is the posterior extension of the quadrate and located dorsal to the quadrate ventral process.
Multi-tissue structure that is a fluid-filled canal in the integument and usually dermal bones, and contains one or more neuromast organs.
dorsal fin middle radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
anal fin middle radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
Process of the sphenotic. The process may project antero-laterally or laterally or ventro-laterally and it has different development in different fish groups. The sphenotic spine is paired.
Superficial and lateral bony projection anterior to orbital region. Sometimes with superficial ornamentation where in direct contact with skin.
Sensory canal on trunk which is posterior to the pectoral girdle and often reaching to or onto the caudal fin. The trunk sensory canal is bilaterally paired.
Sensory canal between and in close proximity to the trunk sensory canal and anteriorly with the otic and preoperculo-mandibular sensory canals. The post-otic sensory canal is bilaterally paired.
Anatomical cluster that consists of a bulla formed by the exoccipital and basioccipital bones, and surrounds the lagena.
Multi-tissue structure composed of enameloid and dentine surrounding a pulp cavity, and found either attached to dermal bone or freely in the skin.
Odontode that is attached to dermal bone.
Odontode that is attached to the skin and without association to dermal bone.
Tooth that is attached to the premaxilla.

Sensory canal between and in close proximity posteriorly with the post-otic and preoperculo-mandibular sensory canals, and anteriorly with the supraorbital and infraorbital sensory canals. The otic sensory canal is bilaterally paired.
Sensory canal that crosses over the dorsal midline and in close proximity to the contralateral post-otic sensory canals. The supratemporal sensory canal is unpaired.
Tooth that is attached to the ectopterygoid bone.
Tooth that is attached to the entopterygoid bone.
Most anterior pharyngobranchial cartilage, located medial to the epibranchials.
Most anterior pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials.
Most posterior pharyngobranchial bone, located medial to the epibranchials.
Perichordal bone that surrounds the anterior tip of the notochord.
Dermal bone of the pharyngeal arches usually bearing teeth.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to the basihyal cartilage or bone.
Tooth that is attached to the basihyal tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 2 bone.
Tooth that is attached to the pharyngobranchial 2 tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 3 bone.
Tooth that is part of the pharyngobranchial 3 tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 4, and located anterior to upper pharyngeal 5 tooth plate.
Tooth that is attached to the upper pharyngeal 4 tooth plate.
Pharyngeal toothplate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 4, and located posterior to upper pharyngeal 4 tooth plate.
Tooth that is attached to the upper pharyngeal 5 tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchials 3 and 4.
Tooth that is attached to the upper pharyngeal tooth plate.
Tooth that is part of the basibranchial tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchials 1-3.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 4 bone.
Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 4 tooth plate.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies dorsal to basibranchial 2 bone.
Tooth that is attached to the basibranchial 2 tooth plate.
Neural arch on the urostyle. It does not support a neural spine. Sanger and McCune 2002.
anal fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
Infraorbital that is the sixth bone of the infraorbital series.

Bony projection that extends from the mesethmoid anteriorly. Mesethmoid cornua are paired processes each articulating with its ipsilateral premaxilla and both cornua bounding a median mesethmoid cleft.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and premaxilla. Mesethmoid-premaxillary joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and nasal. Mesethmoid-nasal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and frontal. Mesethmoid-frontal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and lateral ethmoid. Mesethmoid-lateral ethmoid joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the mesethmoid and vomer. Mesethmoid-vomer joint is unpaired.
Bony projection that is mesially-directed and off the anteromedial corner of each mesethmoid cornu.
Ligament that is attached to supracleithrum and basioccipital.
Membrane bone that is fused to supracleithrum and is jointed to basioccipital and exoccipital.
Lateral ethmoid-ectopterygoid ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the ectopterygoid.
The bony shelf above orbit is an anatomical cluster formed by the dorsolateral portions of the lateral ethmoid, frontal and sphenotic bones that forms the dorsal margin of the orbit.
Interopercular-mandibular ligament is a ligament that connects the interopercle to an element of the lower jaw, typically the retroarticular.
palatine cartilage - cartilage that is separate from and anterior to the pterygoquadrate cartilage.
pterygoquadrate cartilage - cartilage that is separate from and posterior to the palatine cartilage.
anterior cartilage of palatine - cartilage that caps the anterior end of the autopalatine bone. It is typically present in adults.
posterior cartilage of palatine - cartilage that caps the posterior end of the autopalatine bone. It is typically present in adults.

Dermal bone that is located in the middle of the upper jaw, independently formed by fusion of tooth bases attached to soft tissue in the middle portion of the upper lip. The median premaxilla bears teeth in adults.
Muscle located in the lateral region of the cheek, linking the lateral surface of opercle with the posterolateral margin of the suspensorium (usually the preopercle).

Ligament that links the tip of the postcleithral process of the cleithrum with either the vertebral column (at the vertebral parapophysis or rib of the sixth vertebra) or with the soft tissue around the postcleithral region.

Pharyngeal arch cartilage, elongate and usually bifurcated posteriorly, located anteriorly on the upper branchial arches, attached to the anterior tips of the first infrapharyngobranchials. It supports rows of gill rakers on each side and is not homologous to other structures in the teleost gill-arch skeleton. One or two mediopharyngobranchials may be present.

Pharyngeal arch cartilage present on the dorsal surface of the middle portion of the upper branchial arches, dorsal to the point of contact between the second and third infrapharyngobranchials. It is round or cylyndrical in shape. Not homologous to the mediopharyngobranchial.

Endochondral bone, which may be ossified or not in adults, located immediately anteriorly to the pterygiophore series of the anal fin. The structure is usually cylindrical, and its plane of symmetry is transverse to that of pterygiophores and fin rays.
Endochondral bone located posterior to the last anal fin pterygiophore. The anal fin stay is a median bone.
Endochondral bone located posterior to the last dorsal fin pterygiophore. The dorsal fin stay is a median bone.
Dermal bone that is located anterior to the caudal fin procurrent rays. Caudal fin stays are unpaired median bones.
Basibranchial bone that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7). Develops in posterior copula cartilage or basibranchial 5 cartilage.
Infraorbital that is the seventh bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the eighth bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the ninth bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the tenth bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the eleventh bone of the infraorbital series.
Infraorbital that is the twelfth bone of the infraorbital series.

Infraorbital that is the last bone of the infraorbital series, carrying the infraorbital canal, and sometimes also the supraorbital, temporal, and/or preopercular canals. The dermosphenotic is sometimes sutured or fused completely to the skull, e.g. to the autosphenotic.
Anatomical cluster that is the series of dermal bones surrounding the orbit and associated with the infraorbital sensory canal.
Joint that articulates the opercle and interopercle. Opercle-interopercle joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the frontal and pterotic. Frontal-pterotic joint is paired.
Caudal principal ray that is the dorsalmost caudal principal ray of the caudal fin.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 1.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 2.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 3.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 4.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 5.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 6.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 7.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 8.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 9.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 10.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 11.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 12.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 13.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 14.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 15.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 16.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 17.
Caudal principal ray that is ventrally adjacent to caudal principal ray 18.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 4.

Bony projection that is the posterolaterally oriented projection on the ventral region of the mesethmoid. Mesethmoid ventral diverging lamellae are paired and posteriorly contact the lateral ethmoid bones.
Process that is the posteriorly oriented, paired projection of the basipterygium.
Foramen that is located in the scapula. The scapular foramen is paired and formed by a ring of bone.
Foramen that is located in the coracoid.
Fontanel that is located between the contralateral frontals and anterior to the epiphyseal bar.
Fontanel that is located posterior to the epiphyseal bar, and typically located between the contralateral frontals and parietals (if present) and bordered posteriorly by the supraoccipital.
Foramen through which branches of cranial nerves V (trigeminal) and VII (facial) exit.
Foramen through which cranial nerve VIII (auditory) exits.
Anatomical space within a bone in which teeth develop.
Replacement tooth trench that is located in the premaxilla.
Replacement tooth trench that is located in the dentary.
Bony projection located on the anteroventral region of the mesethmoid which articulates with the premaxilla.
Foramen through which the superficial ophthalmic nerve passes.
Joint that articulates the dentary and anguloarticular. Dentary-anguloarticular joint is paired.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the sixth centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fifth centrum.
The pre-narial cartilage is a cartilage that is located anterior to the anterior naris.
Fossa where the exoccipital forms the medial portion and the epioccipital forms the lateral margin.

Pectoral fin lepidotrichium 1 is the leading or marginal ray of the fin and articulates with the scapula. Lepidotrichium 1 is commonly segmented but unbranched but occasionally may be a massive strong unsegmented element (e.g., spine).
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the second most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the third most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the fourth most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the fifth most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the sixth most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that, in a linear sequence, is the seventh most anterior pectoral ray that it is usually branched and segmented.
Bilaterally paired dorsal hyoid arch muscle that retracts the maxillary barbel.
Process that is part of the supraoccipital. It is a posteriorly directed and unpaired median projection off the posterior margin of the supraoccipital bone.
Joint that articulates autopalatine and vomer bones. Autopalatine-vomer joint is paired.

Pectoral-fin lepidotrichium 1 with mostly co-ossified and unsegmented hemitrichia that form a stiff and usually thick shaft and enlarged basal processes that moveably articulate with the pectoral girdle. The pectoral fin spine may also result from the fusion of several lepidotrichia that form a stiff shaft.
Dermal bone that is located near the lateral margin of the pelvic fin, and lateral to pelvic-fin lepidotrichium 1.
Dorsal-fin lepidotrichium 1 with co-ossified and unsegmented hemitrichia that form a stiff shaft and enlarged base that moveably articulates with first (anteriormost) dorsal-fin pterygiophore.
Dorsal-fin lepidotrichium 2 with co-ossified and unsegmented hemitrichia that form a stiff shaft and enlarged base that moveably articulates with second dorsal-fin pterygiophore.
Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 3.
Bony projection that is part of the pharyngobranchial 4.
Joint that articulates orbitosphenoid and prootic bones. Orbitosphenoid-prootic joint is paired.
Foramen in the anterior ceratohyal for passage of the hyoidean artery.
Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 2 bone.
Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 1 bone.
Intermuscular bone that articulates with the vertebral centrum.
Intracranial space formed by confluence of supraorbital, infraorbital, preopercular and temporal sensory canals. See also Di Dario (2004).
Modified epicentral intermuscular bone that connects the back of the skull with the pectoral girdle.
Joint that articulates quadrate and hyomandibula bones. Quadrate-hyomandibula joint is paired.
Joint that articulates quadrate and metapterygoid bones. Quadrate-metapterygoid joint is paired.
Foramen for the passage of the olfactory nerve or cranial nerve 1.

Endochondral bone that is located posterior to the dentary, medial to the angular and antero-dorsal to the retroarticular forming the lower jaw. The articular bears a dorso-posterior articular facet for the condyle of the quadrate. The articular is a paired bone.
An anterior extension of the swimbladder that passes through a foramen in the exoccipital; part of the otophysic connection between swimbladder and inner ear.
Fossa that is a concavity on the dorsolateral surface of the skull roof found at least partially on the epiotic (epioccipital).
Foramen through which cranial nerve VII (facial) exits.
Foramen through which cranial nerve V (trigeminal) exits.
Sensory canal anterior to and in close proximity to the otic and infraorbital sensory canals. The supraorbital sensory canal is bilaterally paired.

Sensory canal lateral or ventral to and in close proximity to the otic and supraorbital sensory canals at their union. The infraorbital sensory canal is bilaterally paired and associated with the infraorbital bones.

Sensory canal lateral or ventral to and in close proximity to the otic and post-otic sensory canals at their union. The preoperculo-mandibular sensory canal is bilaterally paired and associated with the preopercle, angular and dentary bones.

Sensory canal lateral or ventral to and in close proximity with the otic and post-otic sensory canals at their union, and anteroventrally with the mandibular sensory canal. The preopercular sensory canal is bilaterally paired and associated with the preopercle bone.

Sensory canal anterior and ventral to and in close proximity with the preoperculo-mandibular sensory canal. The mandible sensory canal is bilaterally paired and associated with the angular and dentary bones.
Dermal bone that is a bony expansion in the integument anterior to or flanking the dorsal fin that is part of and at the distal end of a supraneural or dorsal fin proximal radial.
Nuchal plate that is unpaired and part of the supraneural and in contact, or not, with the supraoccipital crest anteriorly and middle nuchal plate posteriorly.
Nuchal plate that is unpaired and part of dorsal fin proximal radial 1 and usually in contact with the anterior nuchal plate and paired posterior nuchal plates.
dorsal fin proximal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.
Paired nuchal plate that is part of dorsal fin proximal radial 2 and usually in contact with the middle nuchal plate.
Portion of tissue that is part of the caudal fin.
Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 3 bone.
Epibranchial uncinate process that is part of epibranchial 4 bone.
Scale that is associated with the lateral line sensory canal.
Process that is part of the urohyal; it is the posterolaterally directed process located on the ventrolateral margin of urohyal. Urohyal lateral process is paired.
Process that is part of the urohyal; it is the posterodorsally directed and median process located on the dorsal margin of the urohyal.
Ligament that connects the premaxilla to the maxilla.
Ligament that connects the maxilla with the lower jaw.

Caudal procurrent ray that forms part of the anterior dorsal series of lepidotrichia of the caudal fin and may be associated with a neural spine or a epural or a uroneural. A pair of hemitrichia forms each ray.

Caudal procurrent ray that forms part of the anterior ventral series of lepidotrichia of the caudal fin that may be associated with a neural spine or a epural or an uroneural (dorsal series) and with a hemal spine of a preural vertebra (ventral series). A caudal procurrent ray is an unpaired median bone.
Joint that articulates the pterosphenoid and orbitosphenoid. Pterosphenoid-orbitosphenoid joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the parasphenoid and basioccipital. Parasphenoid-basioccipital joint is unpaired.
Tooth row that is on the premaxilla.
Anatomical point that is the apex of a projection or anything long and tapered; can be bony or cartilage
Joint that articulates the interhyal and epihyal bones, or interhyal and ceratohyal cartilages. Interhyal-epihyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the epihyal and ceratohyal bones. Epihyal-ceratohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the ceratohyal and dorsal hypohyal bones. Ceratohyal-dorsal hypohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the ceratohyal and ventral hypohyal bones. Ceratohyal-ventral hypohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the dorsal hypohyal and ventral hypohyal bones. Dorsal hypohyal-ventral hypohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the contralateral ventral hypohyal bones or the contralateral ceratobranchial cartilages. Inter-ventral hypohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the dorsal hypohyal and urohyal bones. Dorsal hypohyal-urohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the ventral hypohyal and urohyal bones. Ventral hypohyal-urohyal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the epihyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Epihyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the ceratohyal and branchiostegal ray bones. Ceratohyal-branchiostegal ray joint is paired.
Postcleithrum that anteriorly articulates with the supracleithrum and/or the cleithrum of the pectoral girdle; most dorsal element in a series of postcleithra.
Postcleithrum that articulates dorsally with postcleithrum 1, ventrally with postcleithrum 3, and anteriorly with cleithrum.
Postcleithrum that articulates dorsally with postcleithrum 2 and, sometimes, anteriorly with cleithrum.
Process on the dorso-posterior margin of the hyomandibula cartilage or bone that articulates with a depression on the antero-dorsal margin of the opercle.
Gill ray is a slender, usually rod-like cartilage within a gill filament and ligamentously tied to its associated pharyngeal arch bone or cartilage.
An artery that passes along the ventral portions of the hyoid arch; supplies oxygenated blood to the pseudobranch.

A pharyngobranchial bone that articulates with the neurocranium dorsally and epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2 ventrally; lies dorsal to other elements of the dorsal portions of the branchial arches.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 1 bone.
Joint that articulates the epibranchial 4 cartilage or bone and upper pharyngeal toothplate. Epibranchial 4-upper pharyngeal toothplate joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone and pharyngobranchial 3 cartilage or bone. Epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 3 joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the epibranchial 3 cartilage or bone and pharyngobranchial 4 cartilage or bone. Epibranchial 3-pharyngobranchial 4 joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the left and right hypobranchial 3 cartilages or bones. Inter-hypobranchial 3 joint is unpaired.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 1 (pharyngeal arch 3).
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 4 (pharyngeal arch 6).
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 5 (pharyngeal arch 7).
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and at or posterior to the juncture of the bilaterally paired ceratobranchial 5 cartilage or bone.
Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebra 2.
Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebrae 3 and 4.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the Weberian ossicles.
Lateral line system on trunk.
Lateral line system on head and pectoral girdle.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 2 (pharyngeal arch 4).
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is ventral, median, and associated with branchial arch 3 (pharyngeal arch 5).
Neural arch that is the anteriormost neural arch.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the second centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the first centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the third centrum.
Rib that articulates with the parapophysis of the fourth centrum.

PreferredTerm: parapophysis + rib of vertebra 3 + rib of vertebra 4

Description: Neural arch that is located posterior to the neurocranium and anterior to neural arch 1. The accessory neural arch is not associated with a vertebral centrum.
Neural spine that is associated with the first vertebra.
Neural spine that is associated with the second vertebra.
Neural spine that is associated with the third vertebra.
Supraneural bone located dorsal to vertebra 1.
Postcranial axial cartilage located dorsal to vertebra 1.
Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates dorsally with the hyosymplectic cartilage or the articulation of the hyomandibula and symplectic.
Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates medially with a median skeletal element and laterally with a ceratobranchial element.
Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 1 element laterally.
Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 2 element laterally.
Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 3 element laterally.
Skeletal element that is ventral, bilaterally paired and articulates with a median skeletal element medially and with a ceratobranchial 4 element laterally.
Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and forms part of the ventral branchial arches.
Skeletal element that is bilaterally paired and articulates laterally with ceratobranchial element.
Skeletal element of the branchial arches located medial to the epibranchials.
Most anterior pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials.
Pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 1 element.
Pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials and posteriorly adjacent to pharyngobranchial 2 element.
Most posterior pharyngobranchial element, located medial to the epibranchials.
Endochondral element that is ventral, median, and associated with a single pharyngeal arch in the pharyngeal arch 3-7 skeleton.
Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 1.
Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 2.
Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 3.
Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 4.
Skeletal element that is median and associated with branchial arch 5.
Anatomical structure that is formed as a hiatus in the muscles covering the anterior chamber of the swim bladder in the area of ribs 5 and 6.
Surface structure that is a fleshy membrane covering part of the eye.
Joint between the left and right frontal bone.
Canal that houses the dorsal aorta.
Foramina that allow passage of occipital arteries.
Foramen for passage of nerve supplying otic lateral line.
Fossa or chamber on posterior portion of orbital region of neurocranium that serves as attachment site for posterior extrinsic eye muscles.
Fossa or chamber on anterior portion of orbital region of neurocranium that serves as attachment site for anterior extrinsic eye musculature.
Fossa of opercle that articulates with hyomandibular condyle for opercle.
Process of the epioccipital that extends posteriorly, is laminar in form and is usually attached to Weberian apparatus.
Dermal bone that is located lateral to vomer off midline of palate. Accessory vomerine tooth plate bears teeth and may be present as one or more pairs.

Scute that is an elongated plate associated with a ligament running between posterior nuchal plate and rib on vertebra 6. Infranuchal scute is paired and develops from its associated ligament and sensory canal tubular ossicle.
Dermal bone that is ring-shaped or cylindrical and surrounds a sensory canal.
Sensory canal that is a side branch between a sensory canal proximally and a pore at its distal end. Sensory canal tubule is bilaterally paired although often imperfectly so.
Dermal bone that is located on midline of snout in skin above mesethmoid and lateral ethmoid bones. Rostral plate bears type 1 odontodes and is unpaired.
Lip that is expanded to form a broad, rounded cup around the mouth.
Barbel that is attached to the anterior rim of the posterior nostril. Posterior nasal barbel is paired.
Barbel that is associated with the anterior nostril. Anterior nasal barbel is paired.
Barbel that is attached to the distal end of the maxilla and that originates on the side of the mouth. Maxillary barbel is paired.
Joint that articulates the left and right basipterygium cartilage or bone. Inter-basipterygium joint is unpaired.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 4 and vertebra 5.
Joint that articulates the orbitosphenoid cartilage or bone and lateral ethmoid cartilage or bone. Orbitosphenoid-lateral ethmoid joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the autopalatine cartilage or bone and maxilla.
Ligament that connects the metapterygoid to the autopalatine.
Lateral ethmoid-autopalatine ligament is a ligament that connects the lateral ethmoid to the autopalatine.
Mesethmoid-premaxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the premaxilla.
Mesethmoid-maxillary ligament is a ligament that connects the mesethmoid to the maxilla.
Joint that articulates the hyomandibular cartilage or bone and otic region cartilage or sphenotic bone, and often pterotic bone and prootic bone. Hyomandibular-otic region joint is paired.
Process that is part of the anal fin lepidotrichium.
Process that is part of the caudal fin lepidotrichium.
Joint that articulates the left and right premaxillary bones. Inter-premaxillary joint is unpaired.
Surface structure that is a portion of skin that projects or hangs from the body.
Tooth row that is on the dentary.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of epibranchial 1 bone, and that usually articulates with a pharyngobranchial element. Epibranchial 1 bone proximal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of epibranchial 2 bone, and that usually articulates with a pharyngobranchial element. Epibranchial 2 bone proximal cartilage is paired.
Pharynbeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 3 bone, and that usually articulates with epibranchial 3 element. Ceratobranchial 3 bone distal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the proximal end of ceratobranchial 4 bone, and that usually articulates with basibranchial 4 element. Ceratobranchial 4 proximal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 4 bone, and that usually articulates with epibranchial 4 element. Ceratobranchial 4 distal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of ceratobranchial 5 bone. Ceratobranchial 5 bone distal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of hypobranchial 1 bone, and that usually articulates with ceratobranchial 1 element. Hypobranchial 1 bone distal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of hypobranchial 2 bone, and that usually articulates with ceratobranchial 2 element. Hypobranchial 2 bone distal cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of epibranchial bone 3 uncinate process. epibranchial bone 3 uncinate process cartilage is paired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that is part of and at the distal end of epibranchial bone 4 uncinate process. Epibranchial bone 4 uncinate process cartilage is paired.
Mental barbel that originates on the chin, in a posterolateral position relative to the inner mental barbel.

Mental barbel that originates on the chin, in an anteromedial position relative to the outer mental barbel. The inner mental barbel is nearer to the mandibular symphysis than is the outer mental barbel.
Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the fourth centrum. Parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.
Ligament that connects one rib to another.
Anatomical cluster composed of one or more bones and tissue that separates the orbits.
Surface structure that is a portion of the integument thickened relative to surrounding area.
Tooth row that is on the maxilla.
Joint that articulates the hyomandibula bone and metapterygoid bone.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 5.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 6.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 7.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 1.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 2.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 3.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 4.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 5.
Centrum that is part of vertebra 6.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage that is a spherical mass of cartilage located between the mandibular symphysis and ventral hyoid arch. Mandibular-hyoid median cartilage is unpaired.

Anatomical cluster that is an outgrowth of the soft tissue around the dorsolateral corner of a branchial arch that is internally supported by a core of rigid cartilage-like tissue. Epibranchial arborescent organ is paired.
Membrane bone extending between a transverse process of the second proximal dorsal-fin radial and the pleural rib of the sixth vertebra. Lateral bone is paired.
Anal fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched.
Pectoral fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched and segmented.
Anatomical cluster that consists of adjacent gill rakers constituting a row and is part of a ceratobranchial or epibranchial element of the branchial arches. Gill raker row is paired.
Surface structure that is a small, fleshy protuberance.

Compound dermal and endochondral bone that results from the fusion of the paired dermal parietal bones and the median endochondral supraoccipital. Forms the dorso-posterior element of the dermatocranium.

Dermal bone that results from the fusion of the dermal posttemporal and the dermal supracleithrum. Forms the upper skeletal element of the pectoral girdle between the cleithrum and neurocranium. Posttemporal-supracleithrum is paired.
Process arising from the posterior or postero-dorsal margin of the cleithrum dorsally adjacent to the insertion of the pectoral fin. Posterior cleithral process is paired.

PreferredTerm: posterior dentation of pectoral fin spine
Description: Process that is tooth-like or thorn-like and arising from the posteriorly-facing margin of the abducted pectoral spine.

PreferredTerm: anterior dentation of pectoral fin spine
Description: Process that is tooth- or thorn-like and arising from the anteriorly-facing margin of the abducted pectoral spine. Anterior dentation of pectoral fin spine is usually present on the proximal and/or middle section of the pectoral fin spine.

PreferredTerm: anterior distal serration of pectoral fin spine
Description: Process that is retrorse, thorn-like and arising from the anteriorly-facing margin of the abducted pectoral spine. Anterior distal serration of pectoral fin spine is usually present on the distal section of the pectoral fin spine.

PreferredTerm: posterior dentation of dorsal fin spine 2
Description: Process that is tooth or thorn-like and arising from the posteriorly-facing margin of the abducted dorsal-fin spine 2.

PreferredTerm: anterior dentation of dorsal fin spine 2
Description: Process that is tooth- or thorn-like and arising from the anteriorly-facing margin of the abducted dorsal-fin spine 2.
Dermal bone that is ventral to the preopercle and bears a portion of the preopercular sensory canal.
Pore that is located ventral to the posterior cleithral process and medial to the pectoral fin. Axillary pore is at the end of a duct from an integumentary gland.
Supraneural dorsal to neural spine 4.
Neural lamina is a median, vertical ridge or bony septum between neural spine 3 and neural spine 4 on the dorsal side of the Weberian vertebra. Neural lamina is unpaired.
Pharyngeal cartilage that caps the medial margin of the palatine at the autopalatine-lateral ethmoid joint.
Nerve that is a branch of cranial nerve VII that passes through or around the suspensorium to innervate muscles and sensory organs on or near pharyngeal arch 2.
Fontanel within the frontal bone near the frontal-sphenotic joint. Lateral fontanel of frontal is paired.
Foramen located on the dentary for passage of the mandibular nerve.
Process that is the dorsally directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 bone.
Process that is the dorsally directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage.
Dermal bone of upper pharyngeal arches associated with pharyngobranchial bones or cartilages, usually bearing teeth.
Pharyngeal tooth plate that lies ventral to pharyngobranchial 4.
Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 bone part of ceratobranchial 5 bone.
Process that is the anterior and medially directed portion of ceratobranchial 5 cartilage.
Bone that is a fusion of the pterotic, posttemporal, and supracleithrum bones.
Dermal bone bearing teeth located between the distal end of the premaxilla and the middle of the maxilla. The hypomaxilla is a paired bone.
Process that is the lateral projection of the parasphenoid arising and articulating with the more dorsal portions of the neurocranium, usually at the level of the prootic.
Dermal bone of the dorsal surface of the olfactory region. Dermethmoid can be paired or median.
Endochondral bone found between the preethmoid and maxilla.
Barbel that originates on the chin.
pectoral fin proximal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin proximal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin proximal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin proximal radial 4 element that is composed of bone tissue.
Process on the ventral surface of the horizontal limb of the coracoid, close to and parallel to the coracoid-cleithrum joint. Ventral keel of coracoid is paired.
Foramen in the bone or cartilage comprising the anterior wall of the orbit, and through which passes at least the deep ophthalmic branch of cranial nerve V (trigeminal).
Joint that articulates the lateral ethmoid and frontal. lateral ethmoid-frontal joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the prootic and pterosphenoid. prootic-pterosphenoid joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the prootic and exoccipital. Prootic-exoccipital joint is paired.
Joint that articulates the basioccipital and exoccipital. Basioccipital-exoccipital joint is paired.
Fossa located on the neurocranium that is formed from portions of the sphenotic, frontal and pterotic bones.
Joint between the right and left coracoid bones of the pectoral girdle.
Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the sixth centrum.
Parapophysis that is the lateral projection from the fifth centrum.
Process that arises and projects posterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Posterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.
Process that arises and projects anterolaterally from parapophysis 4. Anterior limb of parapophysis 4 is bilaterally paired.
Epithelial cell that produces a chemical that triggers antipredator behavior.
Chemical substance that functions as an alarm signal.
Fine ridge on surface of scale, often parallel to the circumference of scale.
Shallow area that exists on the prootic.

Dermal bone that is located on or subjacent to the surface anywhere on the body and that is not part of the general complement of scales, dermal bone of the dermatocranium, postcranial axial skeleton or paired fin skeleton. Bony plate may exist singly, or as unpaired or paired clusters or series.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses.
Joint between the centra, and sometimes the neural arches or parapophyses of vertebra 6 and vertebra 7.

Anatomical space that is the external opening of a gill slit connecting the pharyngeal cavity to the exterior. Gill opening is usually paired and located on the lateral or ventral surfaces of the head.
Centrum that is the fusion of centra 2-4.
Vertebra that is positioned between the vertebra immediately anterior to the first dorsal-fin pterygiophore to the anteriormost vertebra.
Caudal fin lepidotrichium that is distally branched.
Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one type of nuchal plate in an individual.
Uroneural that is the anteriormost element of the uroneural series.
A vertebral centrum that is immediately posterior to preural vertebra 1. Ural centrum 1 is an unpaired median bone.
Opening in the neurocranium to allow communication between the swimbladder and the inner ear.

Anatomical cluster including hypural 3 and more dorsal hypurals that supports the dorsal series of principal caudal lepidotrichia or rays. The upper hypural set articulates or fuses to ural centra 3, 4 or 5 (polyural terminology) or ural centrum 2 (diural terminology) depending on the teleost subgroup. The upper hypural set is composed of unpaired median bones.

Anatomical cluster including hypurals 1 and 2 that supports part of the ventral principal caudal lepidotrichia or rays and that separates from the dorsal hypural set through the hypural diastema. The lower hypural set articulates or fuses to ural centra 1 and 2 (polyural terminology) or ural centrum 1 (diural terminology) depending on the teleost subgroup. The lower hypural set is composed of unpaired median bones.

PreferredTerm: distal cartilage of posterior process of basipterygium
Description: Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal margin or tip of posterior process of basipterygium and projects posteriorly.
Process that is bony and arises from anteromedial corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.

PreferredTerm: distal cartilage of internal anterior process of basipterygium
Description: Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of internal anterior process of basipterygium.

Process that is bony and arises from anterior margin of basipterygium between internal anterior process of basipterygium and external anterior process of basipterygium. Middle anterior process of basipterygium projects anteriorly or anteromedially.

PreferredTerm: distal cartilage of middle anterior process of basipterygium
Description: Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of middle anterior process of basipterygium.
Process that is bony and arises from anterolateral corner of basipterygium and projects anteriorly or anteromedially.

PreferredTerm: distal cartilage of external anterior process of basipterygium
Description: Process that is cartilaginous and arises from the distal tip of external anterior process of basipterygium.
Process that is bony and arises from lateral margin of basipterygium lateral to pelvic fin lepidotrichium 1 and projects laterally or anterolaterally.
Bone that is attached or adjacent to lateral margin of basipterygium and anterior to pelvic fin lepidotrichium 1. The lateropterygium is a paired bone.
Perichondrally ossified bone that results from the fusion of two or more hypurals and support a variable number of principal caudal lepidotrichia. The hypural plate is an unpaired median bone.
Larval stage in some teleosts before metomorphosis.
Process that is a ventral projection from the supraoccipital that extends between the exoccipitals to the dorsal margin of the foramen magnum.

Fulcrum that is large, laterally expanded, paired or unpaired, scale-like, and that precedes the base of a fin. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235

Fulcrum that is a small, paired dermal structure associated with the marginal, leading rays of paired and/or unpaired fins. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.
Postero-dorsal process of preural vertebra 1 or postero-dorsal process of the compound terminal centrum. The pleurostyle is a paired membrane bone.
A vertebral centrum that is posterior to preural vertebra 1 and consequently the most posterior vertebral centra. Ural centrum is a unpaired median bone.
Anatomical cluster consisting of only a bony element or a combination of a bony element and one or more scales, or only modified scales, which lies in a fin fold at the base of the uppermost ray.

Pectoral axillary process is an elongate structure formed by one or more additional postcleithra or modified scales or a combination of both, that is firmly attached to a skin fold above the articular condyle of the uppermost pectoral fin ray or lepidotrichium 1.
A small bone articulating distally with the haemal arch or a short haemal spine.

Dermal bone located on the ventral surface of the skull and positioned between the two rami of the lower jaw. Anteriorly the gular attaches to the symphysis of the lower jaw through fibrous connective tissue. The gular is an unpaired median bone.
Cartilage associated with hypurals.
Median chondrified cartilage bound to premaxillary ascending process by a rostro-premaxilla ligament.
Dorsal fin pterygiophore that is the anteriormost pterygiophore of the dorsal fin.
Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one bony plate in an individual.
Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one sensory canal pore.
Anatomical cluster that consists of more than one lateral line scale.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the branchiostegal rays within an individual.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the epibranchial elements within an individual.
Anatomical cluster that consists of the ceratobranchial elements within an individual.
Anatomical structure located in the hindbrain that receives primary electroreceptor input.
Anatomical structure that is a subdivision of the cerebellum; it is the location of some lateral line nerve synapses.
Anatomical structure that consists of two neuron types: pacemaker cells and relay cells. The medullary command nucleus commands the timing of the electric organ discharge.
Papilla that is part of the mouth.
Multi-tissue structure that is a transient outgrowth of tissue on skin brooding fish that acts as an attachment site for embryos.
Organ that functions in egg deposition.
Erosion channel that radiates out from the growth center (focus) of the scale across and through the circuli.
Scale that forms part of the posterior border of the caudal-fin organ. Pouch scales are usually hypertrophied.
Surface structure that is a small protuberance on the surface of the body. Nuptial tubercles primarily function to facilitate contact between individuals for breeding.

Organ that consists of a pouch located on the ventral caudal-fin lobe, opening posteriorly, and composed of glandular tissue. The caudal-fin organ presumably functions to secrete pheromones during courtship.
