Anatomical cluster that consists of thickened caudal-fin rays modified into a pumping mechanism associated with the caudal-fin organ.
Intermuscular bone that is located in the dorsal and ventral forward flexures of the myoseptum.
Multi-tissue structure that is a cartilaginous or collagenous bar supporting the caudal appendage.
Multi-tissue structure that is region of the body posterior to the last anal-fin ray.
Anatomical structure that consists of a sheet of connective tissue attached to the vertebral column and dividing the epaxial and hypaxial musculature.
Surface structure that is a midsaggital strap of flattened ectodermal tissue extending along the posterodorsal midline.
Ligament that is in the eye and is located at the angle between the cornea and the iris.

CNS white matter, an axonal tract between ventral diencephalon and ventral telencephalon. At 3 d, the anterior catecholaminergic tract includes noradrenergic projections from the hindbrain and dopaminergic projections from ventral dopaminergic neurons. During later development, other catecholaminergic projections may also contribute to the anterior catecholaminergic tract.
Portion of tissue that forms from the swim bladder epithelium at the anterior end of the swim bladder.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 8.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 9.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 10.
Vertebra that is posteriorly adjacent to vertebra 11. May have hemal arch and rib.
Anatomical space which is located beneath the operculum and external to the gills.

Compound endochdondral and dermal bone that results from the fusion of the dermal dermopalatine and the endochondral autopalatine and forms the antero-lateral region of the palate. Commonly, it articulates with the maxilla antero-laterally and with the ethmoidal region medially. The palatine is paired.
Basal fulcrum that precedes a caudal fin lobe. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.
A vertebral centrum that is located immediately posterior to ural centrum 2 (polyural terminology). Ural centrum 3 articulates with hypural 3 ventrally. Ural centrum 3 is an unpaired median bone.

A vertebral centrum that is located immediately posterior to ural centrum 3 (polyural terminology) and may fuse to ural centrum 3 early in ontogeny. Ural centrum 4 articulates with hypural 4 ventrally. Ural centrum 4 is an unpaired median bone.

Vertebra that is incomplete or rudimentary and may bear a rudimentary neural arch and sometimes a rudimentary spine or the neural arch and spine are completely absent. Ural vertebrae are one of the last bony elements of the vertebral column, usually smaller than the preural centra. Ural vertebrae are numbered beginning from anterior (1) to posterior (2, 3, 4, etc.). Ural vertebra is an unpaired median bone.

Ural vertebra that is located directly posterior to preural centrum 1. It may bear a rudimentary neural arch and sometimes a rudimentary spine or the neural arch and spine are completely absent and it may articulate or fuse with hypural 1 (polyural terminology). Ural vertebra 1 is an unpaired median bone.

Anatomical cluster including all segmented-and-branched rays plus one unbranched but segmented ray located at the leading margin in each lobe of the caudal fin (Hubbs and Lagler, 1947) and that associates with endoskeletal elements such as hypurals and hemal spines of preural centra 1 and 2 (Arratia, 2008). Caudal principal rays are counted from the dorsalmost one ventrally. Caudal principal rays are unpaired median bones.

An anatomical cluster of short rays, shorter than the principal ones, which form the anterior dorsal and ventral series of lepidotrichia of the caudal fin that may be associated with neural spines, epurals and uroneurals (dorsal series) and haemal spines of preural vertebrae (ventral series) (Arratia, 2008). The anteriormost procurrent rays are commonly unsegmented, but the posteriormost ones are usually segmented. The procurrent rays are numbered from caudal to rostral direction. The caudal procurrent ray series is an unpaired median series.
An elongate lateral process ventrally placed to the proximal region of the pleurostyle. The pseudourostyle is paired.

Modified neural arch, probably of ural centrum 4, formed by a bony base that may extend along the dorso-lateral surfaces of ural centra and preural centra 1 or 2 and by a well-developed antero-dorsal membranous projection that extends lateral to the base of epural(s) and anterior toward the neural arches and/or spines of preural centra 1 or 2 (Arratia and Schultze, 1992). The stegural is a paired bone.

PreferredTerm: preural centrum 1 + ural centrum 1 + ural centrum 2
Description: Urostyle that is the result of fusion of preural centrum 1 with ural centra 1 and 2.

Hindbrain nucleus which consists of cell bodies whose axons exit the hindbrain via cranial nerve VIII and innervate hair cells of the lateral line and inner ear. The neurons of these nuclei are unusual in that they extend both contra- and ipsilateral dendrites.

PreferredTerm: obsolete peripheral nucleus of ventral telencephalon
Description: Telencephalic nucleus which has migrated away from the ependyma and consists of the central, lateral nuclei and the dorsal and ventral entopeduncular nuclei. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

PreferredTerm: obsolete central nucleus of ventral telencephalon
Description: Peripheral nucleus of the ventral telencephalon which is located immediately lateral to the dorsal nucleus of the ventral telencephalon. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.
Portion of tissue that consists of afferent axons from the inferior olive and synapsing with Purkinje cells within the molecular layer of the valvula cerebelli and corpus cerebelli.

PreferredTerm: dorsolateral motor nucleus of vagal nerve
Description: Motor nucleus of vagal nerve that is located within the dorsolateral portion of rhomobomere 8.
Portion of tissue that grows in from the dorsolateral wall of the otic vesicle, forming a dorsolateral partition between the developing anterior and posterior semicircular canals.
Portion of tissue that is a thickening and reshaping of the epidermal basal stratum cells beneath which fibroblasts accumulate to form the scale primordium.
Muscle which is part of the head.
CNS white matter that crosses the midline within the hindbrain.

Head muscle that originates on the anterior region of the cleithrum and inserts on the urohyal. The hypobranchial forms initially as left and right parts that later fuse together forming a cone shape.
Diencephalic nucleus which is located between the dorsal hypothalamus and the caudal tuberal nucleus and does not contain tyrosine hydroxylase immunoreactive cells.

PreferredTerm: obsolete lateral nucleus of ventral telencephalon
Description: Peripheral nucleus of the ventral telencephalon that has migrated to the periphery of the brain. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

PreferredTerm: medial motor nucleus of vagal nerve

Description: Podocyte that is part of the kidney (mesonephros).
Portion of cranial nerve II where large fasicles of axons from the optic fiber layer come together prior to leaving the eye.

PreferredTerm: obsolete periventricular nucleus of ventral telencephalon

Description: Diencephalic nucleus which is located in the caudal tuberculum. The preglomerular nuclei make up most of the migrated nuclei within the caudal tuberculum. From Neuroanatomy of the Zebrafish Brain.

PreferredTerm: presumptive cardiac ventricle primitive heart tube

Description: Podocyte that is part of the pronephros.
Lateral line canal that that crosses the supratemporal region posterior to the openings of the endolymphatic ducts and connects the lateral canals of each side.
Organism subdivision that is the side of the body possessing eyes.
Organism subdivision that is the side of the body lacking eyes.
Joint that articulates the premaxilla and maxilla. Premaxillary-maxillary joint is paired.
Pharyngeal arch cartilage located between uncinate process of epibranchial 1 and pharyngobranchial 2.
Scale that possesses cteni (discrete spines).
Ctenoid scale with two or three alternating rows of cteni marginally and truncated cteni submarginally. (Roberts 1993).

Neuromast of the supraorbital sensory canal in the nasal bone. It is innervated by the buccal nerve rather than by the supraorbital nerve, which invariably innervates neuromasts of the supraorbital canal. (Johnson and Patterson 1993).
Fin that is an unpaired fin located in the sagittal plane of the organism.
pectoral fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.
pectoral fin distal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.
Joint that articulates the preopercle and opercle. Preopercle-opercle joint is paired.
Surface structure that is a visible mark on the body resulting from pigmentation.
Scale that is smooth-edged, round or oval and composed of acellular dermal bone lacking small spines on the posterior exposed edge. (from http://www.briancoad.com/Dictionary/introduction.htm).
Clear ocular fluid in the anterior segment of the eye. It is produced primarily by dorsal ciliary epithelial cells.
Multi-tissue structure that composes the opaque fibrous outer layer of the eye.
Portion of organism substance that is a gelatinous extracellular matrix structure that fills the vitreous cavity of the eye.
Dermal bone that is typically associated with a fin. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.

Basal fulcrum that is positioned at the dorsal or anterodorsal margin of the caudal fin. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.

Basal fulcrum that is positioned at the anteroventral margin of the caudal fin. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.
Dermal bone that is an unpaired, scale-like structure. Arratia, G. 2009. Identifying patterns of diversity of the actinopterygian fulcra. Acta Zoologica (Stockholm) 90 (Suppl. 1): 220-235.

The mesencephalic veins (MsV) enter the mid cerebral veins (MCeV) at the dorsal midline. THe MCeVs originate at the dorsal midline, proceede lateraly in a ventral direction to drain into the paired primordial midbrain channels (PHBC). ogai et al. 2001., Kimmel et al. 1993
A vascular loop attached to the efferent part of the mandibular arch that forms at 3.5 dpf. Isogai et al. 2001.
The branch of the afferent branchial artery that continues posteriodorsally. Isogai et al. 2001.
The anterioventral proceeding branch of the afferent branchial artery. Isogai et al. 2001.
The vessel between the anterior cerebral vein and the mid cerebral vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
Arteries that irrigate the forebrain and midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
Extend upward from the PCS, branch to provide an arterial feed to the hindbrain, then drain back down into the PHBC Isogai et al. 2001.

The opercular artery arises from the hyoid stump on the first aortic arch, then follows the lateral margin of the operculum (gill covering) ventrally to reconnect into the proximal part of the first aortic arch. Isogai et al. 2001.
Trunk vessel that connects to the primitive hindbrain channel and the basilar artery at the caudal end of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.
Main route for venous drainage of the anterior and mid cerebral veins as well as portions of the primordial hindbrain channel. Isogai et al. 2001.
Vein that drains the dorsal longitudinal vessel and the caudal portions of the venous capillary network of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.
Hematopoietic tissue derived from the cephalic mesoderm. Predominantly produces myeloid cells. de Jong and Zon 2005.
Vessel that connects to the primitive hindbrain channel and the basilar artery at the caudal end of the medulla oblongata. Isogai et al. 2001.
Vein that connects to the hyaloid vein that drains the eye. External to eye. Isogai et al. 2001.
Vessels run longitudinally along the horizontal myoseptum. These vessels are not functional until after lumenization which occurs near 4 dpf. Isogai et al. 2003.
A continuation of the anterior mesenteric artery, which branches out from the dorsal aorta just caudal to the pronephric glomus. Isogai et al. 2001.
The artery that carries blood to the eye. It branches from the internal carotid artery and enters the eye ventrally through the optic fissure. Isogai et al. 2001.
Vessel that branches from cranial division of the internal carotid artery, extending laterally around the rostral end of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

After the primitive prosencephalic artery forms it becomes disconnected from the cranial division of the internal carotid artery and instead it connects to the anterior mesencephalic central artery and the communicating vessels of the palatocerebral artery.

The PLA branches ventrally from the CrDI. It extends rostrally along the base of mid- and forebrain, then loops medially and links to the corresponding vessel from the other side of the embryo. Isogai et al. 2001.
Connect the palatocerebral artery with the prosencephalic artery. Isogai et al. 2001.
Arteries that irrigate rostral regions of the midbrain. They extend between the Basial communicating artery to the anterior cerebral vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
Drains the PLA loop proceeds straight caudally along the cranial midline just above the pharynx, just below the diencephalon. Forms a 'T' with the palatocerebral veins. Isogai et al. 2001.
Vein that drains the median palatocerebral vein into the optic vein. Isogai et al. 2001.
Composed of scattered layers of interrupted elastic lamina. Hu et al. 2001.
Composed of 7-10 layers of helically arranged smooth muscle cells surrounded by a fine network of collagen, reticular, and elastic fibrils. Hu et al. 2001.
Composed of subendothelium with longitudinally oriented collagen, reticular fibrils, elastic fibers, and smooth muscle cells bound by a thin endothelial layer. Hu et al. 2001.
Cardiac conduction system, characterized by slow impulse propagation and prolonged refractory periods.
Portion of the cardiac conduction system, with rapid impulse propagation.
Project rostrally and dorsally from the AMCtA to to irrigate the midportion of the midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
Project dorsally from BCA to irrigate the caudal part of midbrain Isogai et al. 2001.
Unpaired artery departing from dorsal aorta, typically supplying the small intestine

These arteies branch dorsally from both sides of the posterior communicating artery looping up to join with the opposite MtA as well as with both middle cerebral veins at the dorsal midline of the head. Isogai et al. 2001.

The nasal arteries start at the internal carotid artey and travel rostrally, passing along the right and left walls of the nasal sac at the most rostral end of the head. From the nasal sac, the NA flows into the nasal veins. Isogai et al. 2001.
Unpaired artery departing from dorsal aorta that typically supplies the large intestine

An elaborate set of vessels that branche off caudally from the anterior mesenteric artery just after the dorsal aorta. The SBA vascular loops are located on the ventral side of the swim bladder. Isogai et al. 2001.
Positioned in the intraray mesenchym between the hemirays of the lepidotrichia,. Huang et al. 2003.
Lie flanking and just lateral to the fin ray, in the interray mesenchyme. Huang et al. 2003.
Vessels that travel between artery and veins or vein and vein in a single ray.
Vessels that travel between veins in adjacent rays.
Neuromast that is part of the dorsal lateral line. Kimmel et al, 1995. (Also see Anatomical Atlas entry for lateral line by T. Whitfield.)
Primordium that forms the first neuromasts of the posterior lateral line. This primordium travels at 1.5-1.7 somites/hour and deposits neuromast that are polarized along the antero-posterior axis.
Second lateral line primordium. These primordia moves at 0.2 somites/hour and deposite neromasts that are polarized in a dorso-ventral direction.
A migrating group of cells originating from an anterior lateral line placode. The primordium deposits neuromasts and interneuromasts between them during its migration.
A migrating group of cells originating from the middle lateral line placode. The primordium deposits neuromasts with interneuromasts between them.

A surface structure that will eventually grow to form a barbel. The primordium is rich in taste buds. The final location for taste buds present in the primordium is the distal tip of the mature barbel.
Intestinal epithelium which lines the lumen of the intestinal bulb.
Epithelium that surrounds a primary tooth. This epithelium is committed to formation of replacement teeth.
Skeletal tissue that is hypermineralized and aprismatic and deposited by a combination of ameloblasts and odontoblasts that are excluded from the matrix. Enameloid develops from pre-enameloid tissue.
A branch of the 8th cranial nerve that innervates the cristae ampullaris.

PreferredTerm: distal epidermal cap of regenerating fin/limb
Description: Part of regeneration epithelium at the tip of the fin/limb [ZFA,modified].

PreferredTerm: basal regeneration epithelium of regenerating fin/limb
Description: Layer of the wound epidermis that surrounds the blastema in the fin or limb[ZFA,modified].
Iridescent iridophore containing gold reflecting platelets.
Iridescent iridophore containing silver reflecting platelets.
Bile duct that collects from the intrahepatic ducts and feeds into the common bile duct.
Portion of the liver which develops on the fish's ventral side.

An interneuron in the spinal cord. CoPA are bipolar with 'T' shaped dorsal dendrites, have contralateral longitudinal axons that crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner neuron and ascends in the dorsal cord.
An interneuron of the spinal cord. CoSA, have contralateral longitudinal axons that crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner neuron and ascends in the dorsal cord.
A bifurcate interneuron. It is a commissural neuron with both ascending and descending axons in the ventrolateral cord contralateral to its cell body.
CNS interneurons located in the midbrain.
Hindbrain interneuron that is part of rhombomere 7, with 2 ventral neurons in each hemi-rhombomere.
Cranial vasculature where the posterior cerebral veins and the trans-choroid plexus branch form a circuit around the 4th ventricle choroid plexus.
median fin radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
median fin proximal radial element that is composed of bone tissue.
A bifurcate interneuron where the axon projects ventrally, crossing the spinal cord ventral to the Mauthner axons before bifurcating and extending dorsally.
A interneuron of the spinal cord with an ipsilateral axon that extends ventral to the Mauthner axon then turns dorsally and caudally and sometimes has a minor ascending branch.

A spinal interneuron with a dorsal dendrite that extends caudally. CoLA also has midlateral process that extend rostrally and caudally, the axon crosses the cord dorsal to the Mauthner cell and ascends, extending dorsally. Axon has minor descending branch.
Kolmer-Agduhr neurons are ciliated GABAergic neurons that contact the central canal of the spinal cord and have ipsilateral ascending axons.
Fibrous joint connecting the parietal bones.
Is a fibroblast that differentiates from the de-differentiated cells of the blastema.

Interneurons of the spinal cord that arise from the V1 proliferation domain. The CiA neurons inhibit motoneurons, other ventral interneurons and also inhibit dorsal sensory neurons involved in sensory gating,. CiA have ipsilateral axonal projections in both motor and sensory regions of spinal cord.

A portion of tissue formed between the base of the intestinal villi that is part of the intestinal epithelium where intestinal stem cells are located. In the intestine no crypts are present, but, the regions between the villi, the intervillus pockets, have a crypt-like function. Cells are produced in the intervillus pockets and shed from the villus tips.

Capillary that has endothelial cells that provide an uninterrupted lining, and only allow small molecules, like water and ions to diffuse through tight junctions which leave gaps of unjoined membrane which are called intercellular clefts.

Capillary that has pores in the endothelial cells (60-80 nm in diameter) that are spanned by a diaphragm of radially oriented fibrils and allow small molecules and limited amounts of protein to diffuse
Synovial joint that articulates the hyomandibula and the opercle.
Fossa on the pterotic where the hyomandibula articulates.
Muscle that moves parts of the body in a superior direction to an erect position. Antagonistic to depressor muscle.
Joint that articulates the posterior edge of the preopercle horizontal limb with the symplectic.
Space enclosed by the trabeculae cranii. The anterior tip of the notochord extends into the posterior region of the hypophyseal fenestra.
A muscle that moves body parts into an inferior direction or lowered position. Antagonistic to erector muscle.

Immature reproductive tissue that has not undergone final maturation into either testis or ovary. During gonadal development, the gonad may be transiently intersexual where there is a parallel presence of both oocytes and spermatocytes.
A thin layer of smooth muscle immediately beneath the base of the villi which permits the intestinal mucosa to dynamically move and fold.
Foramen in the hyomandibula that allows passage of the anterior lateral line nerve and the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).
Joint that articulates the anterior edge of the preopercle vertical limb and the hyomandibula.
Smooth muscle of the enteric muscle system in which the cells are aligned perpendicular to the lumen of the gut.
Portion of the renal tubule which is just posterior to the distal early tubule.
Simple squamous epithelium that lines the capsule of the pronephric glomerulus.
Fin fold of the pectoral fin bud, resulting from mesenchyme migration into the apical fold.

The functional webs of the paired fins. They arise as a consequence of apical fold (AER) expansion and of migration of the distal mesenchyme. The fin folds are delimited by a dorsal and a ventral striated epidermis. The cells of the epidermal basal stratum are positioned on a basement membrane. Directly beneath the basement membrane of each side there is an array of actinotrichs, fibers of the extracellular matrix which act as supportive elements of the larval fin folds.
Ionocyte located in the gills
Ionocyte located in the integument during embryonic and larval stages.
Integument ionocyte rich in Na,K-ATPase.
Integument ionocyte rich in vacuolar-type H+ ATPase and carbonic anhydrase
Posterior protrusion of the third ventricle.
CNS white matter, axonal tract interconnecting catecholaminergic cell groups in the posterior tuberculum and hypothalamus.
Portion of the pancreatic duct, external to the pancreas body that connects the pancreas with the hepatopancreatic ampulla.
dorsal fin distal radial 1 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 2 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 4 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 5 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 6 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 7 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin distal radial 8 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 3 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 4 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 5 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 6 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 7 element that is composed of bone tissue.
dorsal fin proximal radial 8 element that is composed of bone tissue.
The dorsal part of the ear. Comprises the three semicircular canals, which connect to the utricle.
The ventral portion of the ear. It contains the saccule and the laguena which are the primary auditory organs.
Duct that crosses the midline connecting the sacculi.
Foramen in the inner ear.
Early-forming telencephalic neural cluster. Neurons of the dorso-rostral cluster (drc) extend axons to form the supra-optic tract (SOT) and the anterior commissure (AC). Ross et al., 1992.
Early-forming neural cluster located in the rostral diencephalon. At 19 h, axons arising from the vrc grow caudally to pioneer the tract of the postoptic commissure (TPOC). Ross et al., 1992.

Early-forming neural cluster of the ventral midbrain. At 16 h, axons of the vcc grow caudally to pioneer the medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF), which is part of the larger ventral longitudinal tract (VLT). Later, neurons from this cluster project axons rostrally into the tract of the post-optic commissure (TPOC). Ross et al., 1992.

Early-developing neuronal cluster of the epiphysis. By 24 hpf the pioneer axon of the dorsoventral diencephalic tract (DVDT) has arisen from the ec and grown ventrally. As this axon encounters axons of the TPOC, it makes a near-90 rostral turn and grows rostrally among axons of the TPOC growing in the opposite direction. Ross et al., 1992.

Hemal prezygapophyses are paired, anteromedially directed processes arising from the bases of hemal arches, ligamentously joined to the hemal postzygapophyses of the preceding vertebra. Posterior caudal vertebrae close to the caudal fin lack hemal prezygopophyses.
Part of the forebrain that is ventral to the ventral thalamus and dorsal to the preoptic area. See page 44 of the Atlas of Early Zebrafish Brain Development.
Part of cranial nerve X.
Non neural ectoderm that surrounds the presumptive neural plate and gives rise to neurogenic placodes.
Is a hyoid muscle that inserts at the most anterior basibranchial and also at the posterior ends of the ceratohyals and functions in jaw closure.
Is a hyoid muscle that attaches to the dorsomedial faces of the hyosymplectics.

PreferredTerm: pillar of the anterior semicircular canal
pillar of the lateral semicircular canal

Description: Rod-like internal median skeletal support elememts of the anal fin, which articulate with the distal radial elements.
Radial elements are the internal skeletal supports of the median and paired fins.
Pelvic fin radial elements are internal skeletal supports of the pelvic fin.
Endochondral element that is paired and supports the pelvic fin. The basipterygium has a posteromedial process called the ischiac process (Wietzman 1962).
Rod-like internal median skeletal support elements of the anal fin, which articulate with the lepidotrichia distally.
Rod-like internal median skeletal support elements of the dorsal fin, which articulate with the lepidotrichia distally.
Rod-like internal median skeletal support elements of the dorsal fin, which articulate with the distal radial elements.

Pectoral fin radial elements are the internal skeletal supports of the pectoral fin which develop from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, supports the pectoral lepidotrichia or fin rays and connects the lepidotrichia with the primary pectoral girdle.

Pectoral fin radial element which develops from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, supports a few pectoral lepidotrichia or fin rays and connects the lepidotrichia and distal radial elements with the primary pectoral girdle (scapula and coracoid).

Pectoral fin radial element that sometimes ossifies, develops from the pectoral fin endoskeletal disc, and is located at the proximal region of a lepidotrichium, between its hemitrichia. Pectoral fin distal radial element is paired.
Dorsal fin radial element that is the rod-like internal median skeletal support element of the dorsal fin located between the dorsal fin proximal radial element and dorsal fin distal radial element.
Anal fin radial element that is the rod-like internal median skeletal support element of the anal fin located between the anal fin proximal radial element and anal fin distal radial element.
Anal fin radial elements are internal skeletal supports of the anal fin.
Dorsal fin radial elements are internal skeletal supports of the dorsal fin.
Pectoral fin proximal radial element that is the most anterior or dorsal pectoral fin radial element.
Pectoral fin proximal radial element that is the second most anterior or dorsal pectoral fin radial element.
Pectoral fin proximal radial element that is the third most anterior or dorsal pectoral fin radial element.
Pectoral fin proximal radial element that is the fourth most anterior or dorsal pectoral fin radial element.
Radial element that is part of a median fin.
anal fin proximal radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.
radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.
pelvic fin radial element that is composed of cartilage tissue.
basipterygium element that is composed of cartilage tissue.

dorsal fin proximal radial 2 element that is composed of cartilage tissue.
